The Comprehensive Crisis in Lebanon
Beirut — Looking back, it often seems that there are signs before a financial crisis occurs; however, they rarely clearly indicate the direction of history.
The same is true of Lebanon's current situation, where a foreseeable crisis has plunged the country into a state of high instability.
Since the end of Lebanon's long civil war (1975-1990), its economic and political systems have been supported by external borrowing, inevitably leading to a continuous rise in public debt.
At some point, inflows of foreign capital had to stop. This turning point arrived at the end of 2019, when a series of negative shocks followed one after another.
This "sudden stop" of capital has brought about a severe triple crisis for the country.
The first issue is the balance of payments.
Lebanon's current-account deficit has reached 25% of its gross domestic product, and its small export base is too weak to cover even the necessary costs of imports.
The second issue is fiscal.
Lebanon's public debt now totals more than 150% of its gross domestic product.
Government revenue is collapsing under the pressure of the economic downturn, with a budget deficit already substantial at 10% of gross domestic product in 2019 and continuing to expand rapidly.
Most importantly, Lebanon is also experiencing a banking crisis.
Main banks, as the primary recipients of foreign capital inflows, have heavily invested in Lebanon's sovereign debt (averaging 50% of their investment portfolios), and are now basically insolvent.
These crises together have pushed Lebanon's economy into the abyss.
Companies eager for loans and imports have begun laying off workers or shutting down entirely.
The economic downturn could lead to a depression in Lebanon.
The main source of capital supporting Lebanon's fragile political economy is not oil, but expatriates, who are attracted by high interest rates and a fixed exchange rate tied to the dollar.
It is therefore no surprise that signs of "Dutch disease" are visible everywhere: deposits have grown to more than 400% of gross domestic product, creating a wealth effect that has reduced the national saving rate to an implausible level — 3% of gross domestic product.
Inequality is high and is still rising.
Between 2000 and 2015, the real (inflation-adjusted) exchange rate appreciated by about 50%, greatly weakening tradable sectors.
Due to the lack of exportable goods and services, Lebanon has been losing its educated youth.
But more importantly, the large-scale capital inflows allowed sectarian elites to consolidate their positions through patronage rather than performance.
These elites have siphoned wealth from both the public and private sectors to establish a bloated patronage network.
Although this ensured political stability in this originally chaotic region, it failed to meet basic needs.
Even electricity supply is discontinuous and unreliable, while the broader challenges facing the macroeconomy remain completely unresolved.
The financial crisis triggered a political uprising.
A popular revolution took to the streets, opposing sectarianism and demanding an end to corruption.
Despite this, so far the country's regime has overwhelmingly favored the elite in its response to Lebanon's economic problems, suggesting that the crisis may ultimately be "resolved" with the support of the poor and middle class, further entrenching sectarian politics.
For example, the country refused to introduce capital controls, leaving each bank's major shareholders, including ruling politicians, to decide how to allocate cash withdrawals.
In fact, this allows elites to transfer capital abroad while ordinary citizens struggle to access their deposits.
In addition, the central bank has reduced deposit rates but has not lowered the interest rate on public debt, thereby increasing bank profits.
Despite the continuous decline in international reserves, Lebanon continues to service its external debt, which is mainly owed to domestic banks.
There are signs that it may begin selling state assets at fire-sale prices to elite-linked entities.
Meanwhile, the official exchange rate remained unchanged, allowing elites to access dollars at the low official rate, while ordinary citizens faced the reality of the rapidly declining free-market exchange rate. The current free-market rate is discounted by 40%.
When the country begins printing liras to pay public sector wages, the depreciation will accelerate.
In fact, the central bank has already been paying interest on dollar deposits in liras (dollar deposits account for more than 80% of all deposits), thereby creating conditions to eliminate public debt through inflation.
As the cost of debt reduction is pushed onto depositors through the "liraization" of deposits, the banks' equity is basically spared.
If this scenario becomes reality, Lebanon's middle class will be significantly reduced due to the decline in real wages and pensions as well as the liquidation of savings.
The emigration of educated young people will accelerate, and even the economic interests of the immigrant community — on which this system relies — will also be damaged.
If the sectarian system is to survive under these conditions, it will rule over a poor population system, one that can be controlled by increasingly cheap shelters.
In the end, Lebanon will find itself in a situation similar to that of Venezuela.
In contrast, the establishment of the new republic pushed by the revolutionaries will take a completely different approach.
Revolutionaries want to improve Lebanon, not abandon it.
They believe its performance falls far short of its potential, and performance, elite management, and social justice should replace corruption, nepotism, and inequality.
They hope to establish a vibrant high-tech industry, make agriculture more environmentally sustainable, position the country as a cultural powerhouse, and create greater synergies with the diaspora community.
To achieve these goals, the reform movement hopes to pursue an orderly reduction of public debt, which will be guaranteed by bank equity and involve the forced reduction of deposits held by depositors holding more than 1% of the total deposits.
They support moderate currency depreciation and a complete improvement in the business environment to enhance export competitiveness.
They will seek deep fiscal restructuring, emphasizing the elimination of corruption and increased spending on social programs and infrastructure.
With the support of the international community, including the International Monetary Fund (IMF), the inevitable recession will be mitigated.
The current infighting over the composition of Lebanon's next cabinet is part of a larger struggle in the country's quest for new political solutions.
The financial crisis poses a fatal threat to the country; but it also represents an opportunity for political change.
Lebanon's future remains uncertain.
